CloudFront security and edge functions.

First, certificates. CloudFront serves star-dot-cloudfront-dot-net with a default certificate. For a custom domain, you attach an A-C-M certificate, and it must live in U-S-east-one, regardless of where your origin or users are, because CloudFront reads its certs from the global control plane there. That catches people out regularly. The viewer protocol policy controls the user-to-CloudFront leg: H-T-T-P only, H-T-T-P-S only, or redirect. The origin protocol policy controls the CloudFront-to-origin leg, independently; encrypt at least the viewer leg, ideally both. Geo restriction allow-lists or block-lists countries by I-P geolocation, returning a four-oh-three on a block, and it runs before any cache lookup. And signed U-R-Ls and signed cookies grant time-bounded access to private content, like paid downloads or premium streams.

CloudFront can also run your code at the edge, in two flavours. CloudFront Functions use constrained JavaScript, run on viewer request and response only, execute in under one millisecond, have no network access, cost about six times less, and scale to millions per second. They're for the trivially cheap per-request stuff: U-R-L rewrites, cache-key normalization, injecting security headers, and simple J-W-T checks. Lambda-at-Edge uses Node or Python, runs at all four trigger points, both viewer and origin, executes for up to five to thirty seconds, has network access, and up to ten gigabytes of memory, scaling to thousands per second. Reach for it when the logic needs a network call or a real runtime, like authenticating against a service or complex origin rewrites.

The rule: use CloudFront Functions for cheap header and U-R-L work at the viewer edge, and Lambda-at-Edge when it needs the network or origin-side triggers.
